\section{Architecture}
The debug configuration adds a single \ILA{} core inside a generate-conditional wrapper controlled by a top-level generic. This allows the same \RTL{} source to produce either a debug bitstream (with \ILA{} and block-\mbox{RAM} overhead) or a production bitstream (clean, used in LH3-E onwards) without editing the design files.

\labfigure{LH3B_debug_architecture.png}{0.85\textwidth}{\texttt{ingest\_top} debug wrapper. The \ILA{} core is instantiated only when \texttt{g\_DEBUG = true}. All probe signals are tapped after their source registers to avoid combinational path lengthening.}{fig:lh3b-arch}

\section{Procedure}

\subsection{Step 1 --- Add the debug generic}
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=2em]
	\item Open \texttt{ingest\_top.vhd}. Add a top-level generic:
	\begin{verbatim}
generic (
    g_DEBUG : boolean := true
);
	\end{verbatim}
	\item Wrap the \ILA{} instantiation (added in Step~3) in a generate statement:
	\begin{verbatim}
gen_debug : if g_DEBUG generate
    -- ILA core instantiation goes here
end generate gen_debug;
	\end{verbatim}
	\item Leave all existing datapath logic outside the generate block. The generic only gates the \ILA{}, not the pipeline.
\end{enumerate}

\begin{tcolorbox}[infobox={Why a generic, not a \texttt{define}?}]
	A \VHDL{} generic is evaluated at elaboration time and has no runtime cost. Vivado prunes the generate-false branch entirely before synthesis, so the debug and production builds share identical \RTL{} source and differ only in the top-level instantiation. This is preferable to commenting out \ILA{} lines by hand, which creates version-control noise and is error-prone.
\end{tcolorbox}

\subsection{Step 2 --- Probe points}
The following table lists the 12 \ILA{} probes as wired in \texttt{ingest\_top.vhd}. Probe numbers correspond directly to the port map in Step~3.

\begin{table}[h!]
	\centering
	\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.3}
	\begin{tabularx}{\textwidth}{c l c X}
		\toprule
		\textbf{Probe} & \textbf{Signal / Source} & \textbf{Width} & \textbf{Purpose} \\
		\midrule
		0 & \texttt{uart\_rx\_pin} & 1 & Raw \UART{} input pin; verify serial transitions are reaching \FPGA{} fabric \\
		1 & \texttt{rx\_data} & 8 & Decoded bytes from \UART{} receiver; validate correct decoding \\
		2 & \texttt{rx\_strobe} & 1 & Byte-level strobe from \texttt{uart\_rx}; one pulse per valid byte \\
		3 & \texttt{fifo\_full} & 1 & \FIFO{} overflow flag; asserts when back-pressure from parser exceeds buffer \\
		4 & \texttt{frame\_valid} & 1 & Successful double-\CRC{} frame; primary integration milestone trigger \\
		5 & \texttt{frame\_reject} & 1 & \CRC{} failure; indicates firmware/\RTL{} \CRC{} mismatch \\
		6 & \texttt{payload(23:16)} & 8 & Beacon~\mbox{ID} (frame byte~2); compare to STM32 log (\texttt{0x01}=Target~A, \texttt{0x02}=Target~B) \\
		7 & \texttt{payload(49:48)} & 2 & Packet type from low 2 bits of Modulation Code (\texttt{00}=DATA, \texttt{01}=ACK, \texttt{10}=PAUSE) \\
		8 & \texttt{metadata(39:32)} & 8 & Parsed \RSSI{} byte; compare to interceptor debug log within $\pm$2~dB \\
		\bottomrule
	\end{tabularx}
\end{table}

\begin{tcolorbox}[infobox={Probe count}]
	The \ILA{} core is configured with 12 probe ports. Probes~9--11 are tied to \texttt{(others => '0')} in the current build; they appear in the dashboard as static zero channels and can be ignored.
\end{tcolorbox}

