\subsection{Step 3 --- Verify the ILA core and port map}
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=2em]

	\item \textbf{Confirm the IP core exists.}
	In the Sources panel, expand \textbf{IP Sources} and verify \texttt{ila\_0} is listed. If it is missing, open the IP Catalog, search for \texttt{ILA}, and regenerate with 12 probes at 1024-sample depth.

	\item \textbf{Confirm the component declaration} in the architecture declaration section of \texttt{ingest\_top.vhd}:
	\begin{verbatim}
component ila_0 is
port (
    clk     : in std_logic;
    probe0  : in std_logic_vector(0 downto 0);
    probe1  : in std_logic_vector(7 downto 0);
    probe2  : in std_logic_vector(0 downto 0);
    probe3  : in std_logic_vector(0 downto 0);
    probe4  : in std_logic_vector(2 downto 0);
    probe5  : in std_logic_vector(5 downto 0);
    probe6  : in std_logic_vector(0 downto 0);
    probe7  : in std_logic_vector(0 downto 0);
    probe8  : in std_logic_vector(7 downto 0);
    probe9  : in std_logic_vector(1 downto 0);
    probe10 : in std_logic_vector(7 downto 0);
    probe11 : in std_logic_vector(5 downto 0)
);
end component;
	\end{verbatim}

	\item \textbf{Confirm the port map} inside the \texttt{gen\_debug} generate block:
	\begin{verbatim}
u_ila : ila_0
port map (
    clk     => CLK100MHZ,
    probe0  => (0 => uart_rx_pin),
    probe1  => rx_data,
    probe2  => (0 => rx_strobe),
    probe3  => (0 => fifo_full),
    probe4  => (others => '0'),
    probe5  => (others => '0'),
    probe6  => (0 => frame_valid),
    probe7  => (0 => frame_reject),
    probe8  => payload(23 downto 16),
    probe9  => payload(49 downto 48),
    probe10 => metadata(39 downto 32),
    probe11 => (others => '0')
);
	\end{verbatim}

	\item \textbf{Verify the generate block boundary.}
	Confirm only \texttt{u\_ila} is inside the generate block. All datapath instances (\texttt{u\_uart}, \texttt{u\_fifo}, \texttt{u\_parser}, \texttt{u\_feat}, \texttt{u\_bram}) must remain outside.

\end{enumerate}

\begin{tcolorbox}[warning={\ILA{} Block RAM Cost}]
	This configuration (12 probes, 1024-sample depth) uses approximately 4 \BRAM{} tiles. The Module~2 pipeline uses 2 \BRAM{} tiles for the feature \BRAM{}. Total with the \ILA{}: 6 of 135 available \BRAM{} tiles on the Artix-7 100T. This is well within budget. The \ILA{} overhead is the primary reason to generate a separate production bitstream in LH3-E once debugging is complete.
\end{tcolorbox}

\subsection{Step 4 --- Re-synthesize and implement with debug}
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=2em]
	\item Confirm that \texttt{g\_DEBUG} is set to \texttt{true} in the top-level instantiation or testbench. In Vivado's \textbf{Sources} panel, right-click the top-level and set the generic value.
	\item Flow Navigator $\to$ \textbf{Run Synthesis}. Confirm zero errors. Warnings about \ILA{} probe widths being 1-bit are expected and harmless.
	\item Flow Navigator $\to$ \textbf{Run Implementation}. Confirm positive \mbox{WNS} --- the \ILA{} should not introduce timing violations on a 100\,MHz design of this size.
	\item Flow Navigator $\to$ \textbf{Generate Bitstream}. The output is \texttt{ingest\_top.bit} in \texttt{impl\_1/}; an \texttt{.ltx} probes file is generated alongside it.
\end{enumerate}

\labfigure{LH3B_vivado_synthesis_ila.png}{0.85\textwidth}{Vivado synthesis report showing the \ILA{} core resource usage. The 4 \BRAM{} tiles for the capture buffer should be visible in the utilization section.}{fig:lh3b-synth}

\subsection{Step 5 --- Program the bitstream}
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=2em]
	\item Connect the Nexys A7 via USB. In Vivado Hardware Manager, program \texttt{ingest\_top.bit} from \texttt{impl\_1/}.
	\item Vivado will prompt to associate the debug probes file (\texttt{ingest\_top.ltx}). Click \textbf{OK}.
	\item The \mbox{ILA} dashboard should open automatically. If it does not, go to \textbf{Tools $\to$ Open Debug Probes} and navigate to \texttt{impl\_1/ingest\_top.ltx}.
	\item Confirm that all 12 probe channels are visible in the dashboard.
\end{enumerate}

\labfigure{LH3B_ila_dashboard.png}{0.85\textwidth}{Vivado \ILA{} dashboard showing all 12 probe channels listed and idle (no \UART{} input connected yet). Confirm the channel names match the signal table before proceeding.}{fig:lh3b-ila-dashboard}

\subsection{Step 6 --- Baseline ILA verification (no STM32 connected)}
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=2em]
	\item With no signal connected to the \mbox{PMOD} \UART{} input pin, arm the \mbox{ILA} with a trigger on \texttt{probe2} (\texttt{rx\_strobe}) rising edge.
	\item Confirm the trigger \emph{never} fires. If \texttt{rx\_strobe} pulses with no input, \texttt{uart\_rx\_pin} is floating and picking up noise. Add a pull-up in the \texttt{.xdc} constraint file:
	\begin{verbatim}
set_property PULLUP true [get_ports uart_rx_pin]
	\end{verbatim}
	\item Change the trigger to \texttt{probe6} (\texttt{frame\_valid}) rising edge. Arm again. Confirm no spurious triggers.
	\item Set a trigger on \texttt{probe0} (\texttt{uart\_rx\_pin}) = \texttt{1}. The captured waveform should show the pin held at logic~1 (\UART{} idle state) when undriven.
\end{enumerate}

\begin{tcolorbox}[infobox={ILA Trigger Strategy for Integration Debugging}]
	Use different trigger signals at each debugging layer in LH3-C:
	\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=1.2em]
		\item \textbf{No byte activity?} Trigger on \texttt{probe0} (\texttt{uart\_rx\_pin}) falling edge (start bit). If it never fires, the physical layer is broken.
		\item \textbf{Bytes arrive but no valid frame?} Trigger on \texttt{probe2} (\texttt{rx\_strobe}) rising edge and watch \texttt{probe1} (\texttt{rx\_data}). Confirm the first byte captured is \texttt{0x7E}; if not, the \texttt{0x7E} start delimiter is missing or corrupted.
		\item \textbf{CRC rejects?} Trigger on \texttt{probe7} (\texttt{frame\_reject}) rising edge and capture the full \texttt{rx\_data} sequence for manual \CRC{} computation.
		\item \textbf{Integration success?} Trigger on \texttt{probe6} (\texttt{frame\_valid}) rising edge. Compare \texttt{probe8} (Beacon~ID), \texttt{probe9} (packet type), and \texttt{probe10} (\RSSI{}) to the STM32 debug log.
	\end{itemize}
\end{tcolorbox}

